Cullen's sign following ultrasound-guided transvaginal oocyte retrieval. To describe two cases of periumbilical hematoma (Cullen's sign) following ultrasound-guided transvaginal oocyte retrieval.Case report.University-affiliated teaching hospital.Two patients, 34 and 32 years old, who developed Cullen's sign following ultrasound-guided transvaginal oocyte retrieval.Workup for pancreatitis and coagulopathies. Laparoscopy was preformed in one patient.Resolution of the symptoms.Pancreatitis, coagulopathy, and massive hemoperitoneum were ruled out. Symptoms resided within two weeks.The appearance of a periumbilical hematoma (Cullen's sign) following ultrasound-guided transvaginal oocyte retrieval reflects a retroperitoneal hematoma of a benign course.